description.narrative: Increased equitable access to and retention in quality KG2, formal and non-formal basic education., which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Increased number of children aged 5-18 access quality inclusive early and basic education in a child-friendly and protective environment.

title.narrative: Increased equitable access to and retention in quality KG2, formal and non-formal basic education.

description.narrative: Children missed 323 days of learning during school closures since March 2020. Although schools reopened in September, almost half of schools are still on rotation with children attending in person 2-3 days/week. During COVID-19, programme implementation switched to online and print modalities for accredited NFE and inclusive education. In 2021, 187,264 children (51 per cent female) were supported to access formal/non-formal education. With the MoE, UNICEF continued to implement Learning Bridges, a condensed curriculum with linked blended learning resources for children to continue learning. UNICEF continued to support access to KG2 through expansion of KG2 and Hajati KG2 cash transfers. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:14/01/2022
